      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Historical texts show 'Texican' used for Mexican-era inhabitants, while 'Texian' emerged during the revolution, and 'Texan' became common post-annexation (s7).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>'Texican': Mexican Texas residents, often of mixed heritage</li><li>'Texian': Anglo settlers during Texas Revolution era</li><li>'Texan': Modern term for all Texas residents</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A settler born in Mexican Texas before 1836 might be called a Texican, but after independence, Anglo settlers identified as Texians.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify which term fits a settler living in Texas in 1825 versus 1840.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming these terms are interchangeable across all periods.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p>"
