      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican culture was a fusion of Mexican governance and Anglo settler influences, creating unique social and cultural practices (s2, s7).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans adopted Mexican legal and religious traditions</li><li>Anglo settlers introduced English language and customs</li><li>Resulted in a hybrid Texican identity</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican towns held Catholic mass but also elected Anglo-style local officials.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify examples of cultural blending in Texican communities.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming cultural assimilation was one-way or uniform.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
