    "id": "slide13",
    "eyebrow": "Settlement Patterns",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Empresario Land Grants and Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Mexican government used empresarios to attract settlers</li><li>Land grants offered to empresarios to recruit families</li><li>Texicans settled mainly along rivers and fertile lands</li><li>Settlements formed hubs for trade and defense</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Mexican government incentivized settlement in Texas by granting land to empresarios, who then recruited settlers, including Texicans. These settlements were strategically located near water sources and fertile soil to support agriculture and community growth. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Stephen F. Austin, a famous empresario, brought hundreds of families to settle along the Brazos River, establishing one of the first major Texican communities.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify why rivers and fertile lands were preferred locations for Texican settlements.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all settlers were Anglo-American; many Texicans were of Mexican heritage or mixed backgrounds.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 13",
      "h": "The Empresario System: A Closer Look",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The Mexican government incentivized settlement in Texas by granting land to empresarios, who then recruited settlers, including Texicans. These settlements were strategically located near water sources and fertile soil to support agriculture and community growth.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Mexican government used empresarios to attract settlers</li><li>Land grants offered to empresarios to recruit families</li><li>Texicans settled mainly along rivers and fertile lands</li><li>Settlements formed hubs for trade and defense</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Stephen F. Austin, a famous empresario, brought hundreds of families to settle along the Brazos River, establishing one of the first major Texican communities.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify why rivers and fertile lands were preferred locations for Texican settlements.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all settlers were Anglo-American; many Texicans were of Mexican heritage or mixed backgrounds.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
    }
