    "id": "slide15",
    "eyebrow": "Cultural Interactions",
    "num": "15",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">15</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Interactions</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Relations with Native American Tribes</h2><ul><li>Interactions ranged from trade to conflict</li><li>Some tribes allied with Texicans for mutual benefit</li><li>Territorial disputes often led to violence</li><li>Texicans adopted some Native customs and knowledge</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans had complex relationships with Native American tribes, involving cooperation and conflict. These interactions influenced Texican culture and frontier survival strategies. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans traded livestock and goods with tribes like the Comanche, while also defending settlements from raids.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explain how Texican-Native American relations impacted settlement security and cultural exchange.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all interactions were hostile; many were cooperative and involved cultural exchange.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 15",
      "h": "Navigating Frontier Relations: Texicans and Native Tribes",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans had complex relationships with Native American tribes, involving cooperation and conflict. These interactions influenced Texican culture and frontier survival strategies.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Interactions ranged from trade to conflict</li><li>Some tribes allied with Texicans for mutual benefit</li><li>Territorial disputes often led to violence</li><li>Texicans adopted some Native customs and knowledge</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texicans traded livestock and goods with tribes like the Comanche, while also defending settlements from raids.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain how Texican-Native American relations impacted settlement security and cultural exchange.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all interactions were hostile; many were cooperative and involved cultural exchange.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
    }
