    "eyebrow": "Settlement Patterns",
    "num": "25",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">25</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Empresario Land Grants and Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Mexican government used empresarios to encourage settlement</li><li>Empresarios received land grants to recruit settlers</li><li>Texicans settled mainly along rivers and fertile lands</li><li>Land grants shaped community locations and sizes</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Mexican government granted land to empresarios, who then recruited settlers, including Texicans, to populate Texas. These land grants determined where Texicans established communities, often near rivers for agriculture and trade. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Stephen F. Austin, a famous empresario, brought hundreds of families to settle along the Brazos River, creating one of the earliest Texican communities.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify how the empresario system influenced where Texicans settled and why location mattered.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all settlers chose land freely without government incentives or restrictions.</p></div></div>",
