      "h": "The Empresario System: Catalyst for Texican Settlement",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The Mexican government granted land to empresarios, who then recruited settlers, including Texicans, to populate Texas. These land grants determined where Texicans established communities, often near rivers for agriculture and trade.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Mexican government used empresarios to encourage settlement</li><li>Empresarios received land grants to recruit settlers</li><li>Texicans settled mainly along rivers and fertile lands</li><li>Land grants shaped community locations and sizes</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Stephen F. Austin, a famous empresario, brought hundreds of families to settle along the Brazos River, creating one of the earliest Texican communities.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify how the empresario system influenced where Texicans settled and why location mattered.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all settlers chose land freely without government incentives or restrictions.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
